New York Jewish intellectual community was far larger and more diverse than is commonly thought. In The Other New York Jewish Intellectuals we find a group of thinkers who may not have had widespread celebrity status but who fostered a real sense of community within the Jewish world in these troubled times. What unified these men and women was their commitment and allegiance to the Jewish people. Here we find Hayim Greenberg, Henry Hurwitz, Marie Syrkin, Maurice Samuel, Ben Halperin, Trude Weiss-Rosmarin, Morris Raphael Cohen, Ludwig Lewisohn, Milton Steinberg, Will Herberg, A. M. Klein, and Mordecai Kaplan, and many others. Divided into 3 sections--Opinion Makers, Men of Letters, and Spiritual Leaders--the book will be of particular interest to students and others interested in Jewish studies, American intellectual history, as well as history of the 30s and 40s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexJewish authorsvBiography. 0aIntellectualszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aJewish authorszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aJewish scholarszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aJewszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aJewszNew York (State)zNew YorkxIntellectual life. 0aZionistszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh1 aChyet, Stanley F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jack J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenstein, Ira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldhay Brenner, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldsmith, Emanuel S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator